               <p>236. 
               
                  <persName id="t18311201-236-defend1815" type="defendantName">
                     JOHN 
                     VELLELEY
                  <interp inst="t18311201-236-defend1815" type="surname" value="VELLELEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-defend1815" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-defend1815" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-defend1815" type="age" value="32"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18311201-236-off1256" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-off1256" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-off1256" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18311201-236-cd1257" type="crimeDate">17th of November</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-236-off1256 t18311201-236-cd1257"></join>, 21 lbs. of brass, value 5s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18311201-236-victim1816" type="victimName">
                  George 
                  Green
               <interp inst="t18311201-236-victim1816" type="surname" value="Green"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-victim1816" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-victim1816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-236-off1256 t18311201-236-victim1816"></join>
                  </persName>
             and others, his masters.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM JUDGE. I am a Thames Police-officer. I met a woman in the Commercial-road, on the morning of the 17th of November, carrying something very heavy under her cloak; I stopped her, and found it was ingots of brass - I went to Mr. Green's yard, and saw the prisoner standing outside the gate; he asked me and my brother officer who was wanted: I said, "
               <persName id="t18311201-236-person1817">
                  John 
                  Velleley
               <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1817" type="surname" value="Velleley"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1817" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1817" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            " - he then begged of me not to let the firm know; I said,"We must:" I heard him tell my brother officer, that he got the metal out of the yard, and he acknowledged at the office, that the woman was his wife.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-236-person1818">
                  THOMAS 
                  GRAY
               <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1818" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1818" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was with Judge, and saw the prisoner near the prosecutor's yard; I asked where he got the metal which his wife was carrying - he said he got it from Mr. Wigram's yard, and gave it to his wife to get a trifle.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-236-person1819">
                  NATHANIEL 
                  CATON
               <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1819" type="surname" value="CATON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1819" type="given" value="NATHANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-person1819" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of George Green, Wigram, and Green - the prisoner was nearly four years in their employ, as a journeyman: I cannot swear to the brass, but I believe it to be theirs - I have fitted these ingots to the moulds, and they fit exactly.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I am sorry for it, they have been good masters to me - I have a wife, and two children.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18311201-236-verdict1258" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-verdict1258" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-verdict1258" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 32.</p>
               <p>Recommended to Mercy. - <rs id="t18311201-236-punish1259" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18311201-236-punish1259" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-236-defend1815 t18311201-236-punish1259"></join>
               Confined Three Months
            </rs>.</p>
